.\" nvflux(1)
.TH NVFLUX 1 "February 2026" "nvflux 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
nvflux \- NVIDIA GPU memory clock lock
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B nvflux
.RI [ COMMAND ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B nvflux
is a small setuid-root helper that lets unprivileged users lock NVIDIA GPU
memory clocks via
.BR nvidia-smi (1).
Clock tiers are queried live from the driver; no values are hard-coded.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B performance
Lock memory to the highest supported clock tier.
.TP
.B balanced
Lock memory to the mid-range supported clock tier.
.TP
.B powersave
Lock memory to the lowest supported clock tier.
.TP
.B auto
Unlock memory clocks; the driver manages them automatically.
.TP
.B status
Print the last saved profile for the calling user.
Does not require root or a running NVIDIA driver.
.TP
.B clock
Print the current GPU memory clock in MHz.
.TP
.B \-\-restore
Re-apply the last saved profile.
Validates the saved name before executing; gives a clear error on corruption.
.TP
.B \-v\fR,\fB \-\-version
Print version and exit.
.TP
.B \-h\fR,\fB \-\-help
Print help and exit.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.local/state/nvflux/state
Per-user saved profile name (plain text, mode 0600, owned by real UID).
The directory tree is created automatically on first write.
.SH EXAMPLES
Lock to performance profile:
.RS
.B nvflux performance
.RE
.PP
Check current status (no root needed):
.RS
.B nvflux status
.RE
.PP
Restore last saved profile on login (i3/Sway):
.RS
.B exec \-\-no\-startup\-id nvflux \-\-restore
.RE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Operational error (message printed to stderr).
.TP
.B 2
nvidia-smi not found.
.TP
.B 3
Not running as root.
.TP
.B 4
No NVIDIA GPU detected or driver not loaded.
.TP
.B 5
Unknown command.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR nvidia-smi (1)
